      Pivot to AI (1)
   =20
 =20
A standard story in the modern tech industry is that every entrepreneur, ve=
nture capitalist, etc., was totally focused on crypto in 2020, and is total=
ly focused on artificial intelligence in 2024. The =E2=80=9Cpivot to AI=E2=
=80=9D is a running joke. It=E2=80=99s a joke in part because these things =
seem=C2=A0unrelated:=C2=A0The skills required to build artificial intellige=
nce,=C2=A0the problems that it solves, the potential uses, the actual real-=
world=C2=A0uses,=C2=A0are all so totally different from those in crypto. Th=
e =E2=80=9Cpivot to AI=E2=80=9D can feel like just arbitrary chasing of hot=
 buzzwords.But a tech executive once pointed out to me that in fact crypto =
and AI are deeply related, and in fact the crypto boom (and bust) paved the=
 way for the AI boom. The connection=C2=A0is=C2=A0chips. If you want to min=
e cryptocurrency, you need a lot of graphics processing units, the speciali=
zed computer chips that were previously sold mostly to computer gamers. And=
 if you want to build a large language model, you need a lot of the same GP=
Us. So the crypto boom created a huge demand for GPUs, which led to GPU mak=
ers =E2=80=94=C2=A0by which I mean mostly Nvidia Corp. =E2=80=94=C2=A0scali=
ng up their production of GPUs. And then the crypto bust created a huge=C2=
=A0glut=C2=A0of GPUs, because crypto miners no longer needed them, so compa=
nies that wanted to build LLMs could easily acquire lots of GPUs to train t=
heir models. That led to a transformative improvement in the power of those=
 models. And now we are in an AI boom, with enormous demand for those chips=
. But crypto got us there.I think it is conventional wisdom that this story=
 has worked out better for Nvidia than for absolutely anyone else: It is th=
e principal supplier of shovels in two of the greatest gold rushes of our t=
ime. However! One could quibble. Bloomberg News reports:The US Supreme Cour=
t agreed to use a case over Nvidia Corp.=E2=80=99s crypto-mining revenue to=
 consider making it harder for shareholders to press securities fraud lawsu=
its.Nvidia is seeking to stop an investor suit that accuses the company of =
being deceptive about how dependent it was on revenue from crypto mining be=
fore a 2018 market downturn. The justices said Monday they will hear Nvidia=
=E2=80=99s contentions that the complaint lacks enough specificity to go fo=
rward. ...In the newest case, the shareholders say that in 2017 and 2018 Nv=
idia=E2=80=99s Chief Executive Jensen Huang hid the fact that record revenu=
e growth was being driven by mining-related sales of the company=E2=80=99s =
flagship GeForce GPU product, rather than by sales for gaming.The investors=
 say the cryptocurrency market=E2=80=99s volatility meant the company was e=
xposed to more risk than it was revealing. The company said in November 201=
8 that had missed its revenue projections, sending shares tumbling more tha=
n 28% over two days.Huang at the time said a =E2=80=9Ccrypto hangover=E2=80=
=9D was to blame.=E2=80=9CAnalysts immediately recognized this as a reversa=
l of NVIDIA=E2=80=99s prior reassurances that mining-related demand represe=
nted a small portion of revenues,=E2=80=9D the shareholders told the Suprem=
e Court.Ah yes! Nvidia lulled its shareholders into believing that it was m=
ostly a gaming company, so they bought its stock because they were optimist=
ic about gaming, but really it was mostly a crypto company, and when the cr=
ypto market suffered setbacks in 2018 those shareholders lost money.
  [4]
=C2=A0And nothing else happened after that.No, I=E2=80=99m kidding, Nvidia=
=E2=80=99s stock=C2=A0is up more than 1,700% since 2018, and the drop in No=
vember 2018 is barely visible on a chart. I suppose one day we will have to=
 discuss the legal arguments in this lawsuit, but part of me thinks that th=
e Supreme Court should dismiss it on the grounds of =E2=80=9Cyou are Nvidia=
 shareholders, come on, you=E2=80=99re fine.=E2=80=9D
