      Pivot to AI (2)
   =20
 =20
The big multi-manager hedge funds tend to offer a specific, desirable produ=
ct, and that product is =E2=80=9Cuncorrelated alpha.=E2=80=9D The idea is t=
hat you hire a bunch of talented and hard-working stock pickers and make th=
em pick stocks, but with no exposure to the broader market or to other comm=
on risk factors. So you can=E2=80=99t have market exposure: If you buy $100=
 million of stocks, you have to short $100 million of other stocks.
  [5]
=C2=A0You can=E2=80=99t have sector exposure: If you buy $100 million of te=
ch stocks, you have to short $100 million of other tech stocks. And you can=
=E2=80=99t cheat by getting exposure to other factors: You can=E2=80=99t ju=
st buy small-cap stocks and short large-cap stocks; you have to keep your s=
mall-cap and large-cap exposure neutral. Et cetera: All the standard identi=
fied factors get neutralized out, and you=E2=80=99re left with no exposure =
to anything except the stock pickers=E2=80=99 skill.=C2=A0The pitch to inve=
stors is something like: If you are a big institutional investor, you will =
of course allocate some of your capital to=C2=A0market bets, buying the who=
le stock market or tech stocks or AI stocks or whatever, which will give yo=
u exposure to the broad stock market and to particular sectors that you lik=
e. Those bets are cheap: The fees on an S&P 500 index fund approach=C2=A0ze=
ro, and you can buy cheap factor-based funds that give you exposure to well=
-known risk premiums.=C2=A0But then you should also allocate some capital t=
o the hedge fund, because it offers you a diversification benefit: It promi=
ses a return that is uncorrelated to your general stock market exposure. Wh=
en the stock market goes down, the hedge fund won=E2=80=99t lose money, bec=
ause it carefully hedges out all market exposure. You get your various mark=
et exposures =E2=80=94=C2=A0your betas =E2=80=94 elsewhere, cheaply, and yo=
u pay the hedge fund a ton of fees for alpha.This pitch has been very succe=
ssful. But on the other hand, if you are giant multi-manager hedge fund, it=
 can feel a bit wasteful. After all:=09Your clients are allocating a lot of=
 their capital to betting on the stock market and on particular hot sectors=
.=09You would like more of their money.=09Your employees are all hired for =
their skill at picking stocks.Why aren=E2=80=99t you=C2=A0giving the client=
s their general stock exposure? Or part of it, anyway.
  [6]
=C2=A0It is tempting to offer the clients=C2=A0two (separate)=C2=A0products=
: uncorrelated alpha, and also a fund that buys the hot stocks. Bloomberg N=
ews reports:Steve Cohen=E2=80=99s Point72 Asset Management is seeking to ra=
ise about $1 billion for a new stock-picking hedge fund focused on artifici=
al intelligence, according to people familiar with the matter.The fund will=
 bet on and against AI hardware and semiconductor companies globally and wi=
ll be the firm=E2=80=99s first new hedge fund in decades, the people said, =
asking not to be identified because the information is private. Point72 cur=
rently has a main hedge fund along with some venture capital vehicles.Cohen=
 has said he expects the impact of AI to be =E2=80=9Ctransformational=E2=80=
=9D and that it has the power to change how companies work and save them mi=
llions of dollars. =E2=80=A6While Point72=E2=80=99s main fund is strictly m=
arket-neutral, the new vehicle will have a more flexible mandate, meaning i=
t may hold some longer-biased positions not typically held in the main fund=
.In its core product, investors are absolutely not paying Point72 to make b=
ig bets that AI will be transformational; they are paying Point72 for marke=
t-neutral uncorrelated alpha. But if Point72=C2=A0thinks=C2=A0that AI will =
be transformational, and if investors=C2=A0want=C2=A0to pay it to make thos=
e bets, it should take their money.
