or retaliate against their employees for reporting misconduct to the SEC.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Many firms have employees sign=C2=
=A0nondisclosure agreements that say something like =E2=80=9Cyou won=E2=80=
=99t tell anyone any confidential information you get at our firm, and if y=
ou do we can sue you.=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The=
 SEC interprets that as a threat against whistleblowers: Theoretically, you=
 can read it to mean =E2=80=9Cyou won=E2=80=99t tell anyone (including the =
SEC)=C2=A0any confidential information you get at our firm (including about=
 our crimes), and if you do we can sue you (to retaliate for your whistlebl=
owing).=E2=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Therefore, those =
NDAs are illegal, and the SEC can extract fines from firms that have them, =
even if those firms would never dream of enforcing those NDAs against whist=
leblowers.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a good enough rack=
et for the SEC that the CFTC is getting into it:</p><blockquote><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">Trafigura required its employees to sign employment agree=
