rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">running joke</a>. It=E2=
=80=99s a joke in part because these things seem=C2=A0<em>unrelated</em><em=
>:=C2=A0</em>The skills required to build artificial intelligence,=C2=A0the=
 problems that it solves, the potential uses, the <em>actual </em>real-worl=
d=C2=A0uses,=C2=A0are all so totally different from those in crypto. The =
=E2=80=9Cpivot to AI=E2=80=9D can feel like just arbitrary chasing of hot b=
uzzwords.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But a tech executive once pointed=
 out to me that in fact crypto and AI are deeply related, and in fact the c=
rypto boom (and bust) paved the way for the AI boom. The connection=C2=A0is=
=C2=A0<em>chips</em>. If you want to mine cryptocurrency, you need a lot of=
 graphics processing units, the specialized computer chips that were previo=
usly sold mostly to computer gamers. And if you want to build a large langu=
age model, you need a lot of the same GPUs. So the crypto boom created a hu=
ge demand for GPUs, which led to GPU makers =E2=80=94=C2=A0by which I mean =
mostly Nvidia Corp. =E2=80=94=C2=A0scaling up their production of GPUs. And=
 then the crypto bust created a huge=C2=A0<em>glut=C2=A0</em>of GPUs, becau=
se crypto miners no longer needed them, so companies that wanted to build L=
LMs could easily acquire lots of GPUs to train their models. That led to a =
transformative improvement in the power of those models. And now we are in =
an AI boom, with enormous demand for those chips. But crypto got us there.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think it is conventional wisdom that this=
 story has worked out better for Nvidia than for absolutely anyone else: It=
 is the principal supplier of shovels in two of the greatest gold rushes of=
 our time. However! One could quibble. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/35759932.283292/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZX=
dzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDYtMTcvbnZpZGlhLWdldHMtc3VwcmVtZS1jb3VydC1yZXZpZXctb=
